(303, 1, '2020-01-27 08:28:17', '2020-01-27 08:28:17', 'Our research activities include understanding the epidemiology, immunology, evolution and the disease burden of viral pathogens. We are currently investigating why rotavirus vaccines underperform in low-income settings. We are continuously assessing the effectiveness of Rotarix® rotavirus vaccine following its introduction into Malawi’s childhood immunisation program, determining the immune responses induced by rotavirus vaccination and rotavirus natural infection, deducing host factors that could be associated with vaccine responses, assessing the impact of rotavirus vaccine introduction on the circulating rotavirus strains, and also assessing the immunogenicity and efficacy of new rotavirus vaccines in Malawian children. In addition, we are investigating the origins and characterising the genetic epidemiology of SARS-CoV2 strains that are circulating in Malawi through nucleotide sequencing approaches.', 'Virology', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'virology', '', '', '2020-08-13 15:10:57', '2020-08-13 15:10:57', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=research&#038;p=303', 0, 'research', '', 0),
(304, 1, '2020-01-27 08:28:11', '2020-01-27 08:28:11', '', 'Rotavirus', 'Rotavirus vaccine - administration of antigenic material (vaccine) to stimulate an individual\'s immune system to develop adaptive immunity to a pathogen.', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'rotavirus', '', '', '2020-01-27 08:28:11', '2020-01-27 08:28:11', '', 303, 'http://127.0.0.1/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/iStock-954824754.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(305, 1, '2020-01-27 08:41:05', '2020-01-27 08:41:05', 'Agness is a pre-PhD research intern within the Viral Immunology research group under the supervision of Dr Kondwani Jambo and Prof Henry Mwandumba. She obtained a Bachelor of Science degree in Medical Laboratory Technology from the University of Malawi (College of Medicine), and a Master of Life Sciences in Biomolecular Sciences from Tohoku University (Japan), in 2011 and 2018, respectively.\r\n\r\nHer internship is linked to a project that is investigating the phenotype and functional profile of HIV-specific CD8+ T cells in gut. She is also involved in development and optimization of tools to detect HIV-infected cells in the blood, lung and gut. Agness’s main interest is understanding the mechanism of HIV reservoir formation in tissues.\r\n\r\nHer immediate goal is to pursue a PhD in Immunology and her long-term career goal is to become an independent researcher in Africa focusing on developing of strategies for HIV cure.', 'Agness Ethel Lakudzala', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'agness-ethel-lakudzala', '', '', '2020-03-11 11:10:41', '2020-03-11 11:10:41', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=305', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
