(307, 1, '2020-01-27 08:45:26', '2020-01-27 08:45:26', 'Alice is the Research Nurse within the Viral Immunology Group. She obtained a diploma in Nursing and Midwifery from Joseph College of Nursing in 2011. She is in the penultimate year of a Bachelor of Science Degree in Social Sciences-Development Studies at Catholic University of Malawi. Leah is registered with Malawi Nurses and Midwifery Council of Malawi and has clinical trial experience.\r\n\r\nCurrently, she is part of a study focusing on investigating factors that explain ongoing high prevalence of pneumococcal colonisation in HIV-infected adults on antiretroviral therapy. Alice’s long-term goal is to help contribute to the reduction of high disease burden in Malawi.', 'Alice Kusakala Kalirani', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'alice-kusakala-kalirani', '', '', '2020-03-11 11:11:13', '2020-03-11 11:11:13', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=307', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
(308, 1, '2020-01-27 08:46:38', '2020-01-27 08:46:38', 'Dr. Isaac Thom Shawa is a Senior Lecturer in Medical Virology at the University of Malawi College of Medicine, Faculty of Biomedical Science and Health Professions (BMSHP); and a Deputy Group Head for Virology Research Group. He is currently conducting postdoctoral research at the Malawi-Liverpool Wellcome Trust Clinical Research Programme (MLW). He has supervised quite a considerable number of both undergraduate and postgraduate students.\r\nDr. Shawa is a Virologist and broadly interested in host-viral interactions in understanding the viral pathogenesis and their elicited immune responses. His research interests are shaped by the emerging trend towards the multi-disciplinary approach that can facilitate understanding of host immune responses to various micro-organisms. His PhD research mainly focused on the different strategies to identify characteristics of Hepatitis C virus (HCV) resistance; and the possible immunological mechanisms that protect the HCV exposed uninfected population. His current research projects include identification of factors that contribute to low Rotavirus vaccine efficacy in developing countries including Malawi as opposed to developed countries; and molecular characterisation of hepatitis viruses in Malawi.\r\n\r\n2. Education background – Current level of education, education obtained in the past from Bachelors level.\r\n\r\nDr. Shawa holds a PhD in virology. He awarded a MRC/NHS Trust scholarship for a full-time PhD studies at the University of Plymouth in collaboration with Imperial College London in the United Kingdom. Prior to that, he was also a recipient of a prestigious Commonwealth Scholarship to pursue postgraduate studies at the University of Liverpool in the UK. He did his undergraduate studies both in Malawi and South Africa.\r\n\r\n3. Long term goals - e.g. project to pursue, attaining further education.\r\n\r\nDr. Shawa would like to continue sharing his knowledge and experience through teaching, research, and publications. Overall, he would like to be involved in the following:\r\n- Learn new scientific/research skills in immunology.\r\n- Gain leadership and managerial experience.\r\n- Win some research grants.\r\n- Be able to attract students of high calibre who can help produce excellent research.\r\n- Become a Professor.\r\n- Write a book.', 'Dr. Isaac Thom Shawa', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'dr-isaac-thom-shawa', '', '', '2020-03-11 10:55:13', '2020-03-11 10:55:13', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=308', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
(309, 1, '2020-01-27 08:52:04', '2020-01-27 08:52:04', 'Oscar Kanjerwa is a Laboratory Technician at MLW for RV3-BB vaccine trial the Virology Research group. In this project, we are testing RV3-BB vaccine for its safety and immunogenicity as primary end points. Prior this, Oscar also worked in the vaccine surveillance study which was assessing vaccine effectiveness of the rotavirus vaccine that was intoruduced in Malawi in October 2012.\r\n\r\nOscar has a Diploma in Biomedical Sciences from the Malawi Adventist University (Malamulo College of Health Sciences) and a Certificate in Education from Lilongwe Teachers College. He is currently pursuing a BSc. in Public Health at Share World Open University.\r\n\r\nHis long-term goal is to become a vibrant researcher in Molecular Biology and contribute a lot in the area of disease prevention at national and international level.', 'Oscar Thom Kanjerwa', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'oscar-thom-kanjerwa', '', '', '2020-03-11 10:56:40', '2020-03-11 10:56:40', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=309', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
