(1032, 0, '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Study findings have revealed that men could be reporting to care facilities late resulting in delayed Tuberculosis diagnosis, thereby contributing to on-going transmission of the disease in community. The study which was conducted in 2011 by Malawi Liverpool Wellcome Trust and Malawi College of Medicine researchers in Blantyre, in conjunction with the Human Sciences Research Council in South Africa, attributes men’s behaviour to several factors including their expectations and roles to provide for the family</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">.According to Jeremiah Chikovore, Principle Investigator of the study, men don’t want to be seen lying down as a result of an illness, nor can they afford to spend long hours seeking care when they would rather be working to support their families.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Men at risk of reporting late to care facilities for TB diagnosis', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'men-at-risk-of-reporting-late-to-care-facilities-for-tb-diagnosis', '', '', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/men-at-risk-of-reporting-late-to-care-facilities-for-tb-diagnosis/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1033, 0, '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '<p>A cluster randomized trial in Blantyre by Malawi Liverpool Wellcome Trust (MLW) and College of Medicine, which commenced in 2010, has shown that more people are willing to do self testing for HIV within the confines of their homes.<br /><span style=\"line-height: 1.3em\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.3em\">The study reveals that people prefer self testing, because of its privacy and convenience. So far 12,970 people recorded in the study are reported to have done self-testing within the townships of Ndirande, Likhubula and Chilomoni in Blantyre, representing a 78 percent uptake of self-testing.</span></p>\r\n<p>According to the Trial Coordinator Augustine Choko, people including community leaders have welcomed the study which commenced in 2010 for many reasons.</p>\r\n', 'HIV Self-testing gets positive response in Blantyre', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hiv-self-testing-gets-positive-response-in-blantyre', '', '', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '2013-09-18 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/hiv-self-testing-gets-positive-response-in-blantyre/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1034, 0, '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Emanuele Giorgi has become the European winner of the Young Statistician’s Showcase prize of the International Biometric Society\'s world conference, winning a&nbsp; $3000 prize for his research paper on malaria prevalence mapping aimed at fighting malaria in sub-Saharan Africa.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />Emanuele, who is doing a PhD in Statistics and Epidemiology at Lancaster University with supervisors Professor Peter Diggle and Dr. Anja Terlouw from MLW, has developed a new statistical method to improve malaria burden estimations from surveillance data. As part of his PhD he has spent several months in Malawi at MLW.</p>\r\n', 'PhD student wins international prize', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'phd-student-wins-international-prize', '', '', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/phd-student-wins-international-prize/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1035, 0, '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In a newly published <a href=\"http://brain.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/awu001?ijkey=8GUqCFlr39QXAj4&amp;keytype=ref\">review paper</a> on cerebral malaria in children, Dr. Ian MacCormick and colleagues, conclude that the retina could be a useful tool to better understand cerebral malaria and may lead to improved treatment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />Cerebral malaria is a dangerous illness for children in Malawi, and a frequent cause of death. Despite many years of research, it is still not entirely clear what happens in cerebral malaria that causes some children to die while others survive. This is partly because it is difficult to study the brain - the brain is inside the skull and it is not easy to reach with a microscope or other tools often used in medical research. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Similarities between the eye retina and brain could help understanding of Cerebral Malaria', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'similarities-between-the-eye-retina-and-brain-could-help-understanding-of-cerebral-malaria', '', '', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '2014-04-10 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/similarities-between-the-eye-retina-and-brain-could-help-understanding-of-cerebral-malaria/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1036, 0, '2014-04-17 00:00:00', '2014-04-17 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A newly published paper on schistosomiasis in children, by Dr. Helen Poole and colleagues, has found a considerable burden of the disease in young children in Chikhwawa district, highlighting the need for a more in-depth evaluation of the scale of the problem in young children in Malawi. Young children are currently not included in the national Malawi schistosomiasis control programme, which provides mass drug treatment with praziquantel (MDA) to school-aged children only.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0.11in;text-align: justify\" lang=\"en-GB\">Dr Helen Poole (who came to MLW as an LSTM MSc student) and MLW field staff examined pre-school-age children (PSAC) below 5 years of age and their mothers in Chikhwawa district. They found that approximately half of the examined pre-school-age children were infected and identified both urogenital and intestinal forms.</p>\r\n', 'High burden of schistosomiasis in pre-school-age children in Chikhwawa district', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'high-burden-of-schistosomiasis-in-pre-school-age-children-in-chikhwawa-district', '', '', '2014-04-17 00:00:00', '2014-04-17 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/high-burden-of-schistosomiasis-in-pre-school-age-children-in-chikhwawa-district/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1037, 0, '2014-05-04 00:00:00', '2014-05-04 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A distinctive genetic ‘signature’ found in the blood of children with tuberculosis (TB) offers new hope for improved diagnosis of the disease, reveals a&nbsp; recently published study in the New England Journal of Medicine.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;line-height: normal;margin-bottom: 0pt\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;line-height: normal;margin-bottom: 0pt\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'\">It is hoped that the findings could be used to develop cheap, quick and effective diagnostic test. The study which was conducted in Malawi, Kenya, and South Africa, showed that the disease can be identified in over 80 percent of cases by looking at 51 specific genes in the blood of affected children. By examining blood samples of children to see which genes were activated or suppressed in those with the disease, the researchers found that TB could be distinguished from other diseases.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;line-height: normal;margin-bottom: 0pt\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'\">.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;line-height: normal;margin-bottom: 0pt\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n', 'New Genetic Discovery could Improve Diagnosis of Childhood TB', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-genetic-discovery-could-improve-diagnosis-of-childhood-tb', '', '', '2014-05-04 00:00:00', '2014-05-04 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/new-genetic-discovery-could-improve-diagnosis-of-childhood-tb/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1038, 0, '2014-05-23 00:00:00', '2014-05-23 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A recent paper published by <a href=\"http://www.malariajournal.com/content/13/1/138/abstract\">Dr. Eva Maria Hodel and colleagues</a> highlights the differences in effectiveness between the highly controlled settings under which antimalarial drugs are tested and the real-life settings and ways they may be used in practice.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">As part of an MRC methodology research grant held by Drs Ian Hastings &amp; Anja Terlouw, Dr Hodel used mathematical models to simulate realistic antimalarial drug treatment practices in real-life settings that may either be impossible, difficult or unethical to test in trials.</p>\r\n', 'Optimising the Programmatic Deployment of Antimalarials using Pharmacological modelling', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'optimising-the-programmatic-deployment-of-antimalarials-using-pharmacological-modelling', '', '', '2014-05-23 00:00:00', '2014-05-23 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/optimising-the-programmatic-deployment-of-antimalarials-using-pharmacological-modelling/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1039, 0, '2014-06-13 00:00:00', '2014-06-13 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">HIV Self-testing has been recognized as one of the best ways of offering opportunity to people especially from resource poor communities to test themselves in private and know their HIV status which has potential benefit of helping them to live a positive life.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">According to research findings, one of the main obstacles to improving HIV/TB control is low uptake of regular HIV testing by many adults in Africa.</p>\r\n', '‘HIV Self-Testing’ receives International Recognition', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hiv-self-testing-receives-international-recognition', '', '', '2014-06-13 00:00:00', '2014-06-13 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/hiv-self-testing-receives-international-recognition/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1040, 0, '2014-07-02 00:00:00', '2014-07-02 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Construction of a new research facility in Chikhwawa will start soon as MLW has received a £160,000 (MWK 107 milllion) grant from the Wellcome Trust for the work.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />Once completed, the new research facility will support the growing number of research activities in Chikhwawa District.<br />The funding will allow the construction of a dedicated clinical research building on the grounds of Chikhwawa hospital, thus developing the new MLW Chikhwawa child survival Initiative to the next level.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Chikhwawa Building Grant to Advance Research Activities at MLW', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'chikhwawa-building-grant-to-advance-research-activities-at-mlw', '', '', '2014-07-02 00:00:00', '2014-07-02 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/chikhwawa-building-grant-to-advance-research-activities-at-mlw/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1041, 0, '2014-07-21 00:00:00', '2014-07-21 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">An Exhibition at the Wellcome Collection depicting a variety of journeys of artists across medical research centres funded by the Wellcome Trust closed doors in March this year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br /><a href=\"http://www.welcomecollection.org/foreignbodies\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">The Foreign Bodies, Common Ground exhibition</span></a>&nbsp;offered a unique exploration of global health, by bringing together artworks including painting, photography, sculpture, film and performance, made during residencies at medical research centres funded by the Wellcome Trust in Kenya, Malawi, South Africa, Thailand, Vietnam and the UK.</p>\r\n', 'Artists explore global Health at Wellcome Collection', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'artists-explore-global-health-at-wellcome-collection', '', '', '2014-07-21 00:00:00', '2014-07-21 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/artists-explore-global-health-at-wellcome-collection/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1042, 0, '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Pneumonia is one of the leading causes of child morbidity in Malawi with thousands of children under the age of five reported to be dying every year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Exposure to smoke produced when biomass fuels (animal or plant material) are burned in open fires is a major risk factor in more cases of pneumonia.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In Malawi, where at least 95% of households depend on biomass as their main source of fuel, biomass smoke exposure is likely to be responsible for a substantial burden of this disease.</p>\r\n', 'CAPS study receives positive reaction in Chikhwawa', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'caps-study-receives-positive-reaction-in-chikhwawa', '', '', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/caps-study-receives-positive-reaction-in-chikhwawa/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1043, 0, '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">As Ebola continues to spread in West Africa with latest information from the <a href=\"http://www.dw.de/world-health-organization-ups-west-africa-ebola-deaths/a-17868523\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">World Health Organisation</span></a> WHO showing that at least 1, 350 people have died from the disease, <a href=\"http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/Media-office/Press-releases/2014/WTP057180.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Wellcome Trust</span></a> on 21st of August 2014 announced a multi-million pound emergency funding for research into the disease and separate £40 million investment in African research.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">It is believed that the research would help contain the epidemic in West Africa and future outbreaks of the infectious disease.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The Ebola, named after the Ebola River in Zaire - dates back to 1976 - when it first emerged in Sudan and Zaire. The virus has been around in West Africa but starting from July this year, the virus has spread rapidly.</p>\r\n', 'Wellcome Trust announces funding for Ebola', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'wellcome-trust-announces-funding-for-ebola', '', '', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '2014-08-25 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/wellcome-trust-announces-funding-for-ebola/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1044, 0, '2014-09-09 00:00:00', '2014-09-09 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In order to equip biomedical researchers and students with Bioinformatics and its application to biological research, Malawi-Liverpool-Wellcome Trust (MLW) is working towards building the capacity of the bioinformatics research team through trainings.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />Recently, the team conducted a two-day training workshop for Bioinformatics researchers with primary focus on basics of its technologies used to generate high-throughput genomic data, fundamental application and how to anayse and visualize data using widely software packages.</p>\r\n', 'MLW researchers drilled on basics of Bioinformatics', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mlw-researchers-drilled-on-basics-of-bioinformatics', '', '', '2014-09-09 00:00:00', '2014-09-09 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/mlw-researchers-drilled-on-basics-of-bioinformatics/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1045, 0, '2014-10-01 00:00:00', '2014-10-01 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">People who consume excessive salt are more likely to develop hypertension than those who do not, say medical experts.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />They were speaking at an Urban Science Café organised by Malawi-Liverpool-Wellcome Trust (MLW) on Wednesday, 24th September.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />A lead expert in non-communicable diseases in Malawi, Professor Moffat Nyirenda explained that excessive salt puts people at risk of developing hypertension.</p>\r\n', '‘Too much salt bad for your health’ - Medical experts', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'too-much-salt-bad-for-your-health-medical-experts', '', '', '2014-10-01 00:00:00', '2014-10-01 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/too-much-salt-bad-for-your-health-medical-experts/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1046, 0, '2014-10-16 00:00:00', '2014-10-16 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">People infected with HIV but are stable and taking a combination of potent antiretroviral drugs (known as ART), are still more susceptible to developing TB disease than those who are not HIV-infected because of problems with TB-specific immune responses in their lungs, a new study has revealed<br />&nbsp;<br />The study, conducted by researchers at the Malawi-Liverpool Wellcome Trust Clinical Research Programme, explains why people taking ART who have undetectable concentration of HIV viruses in their blood and a high T cell count (indicating a good response to ART and a strong immune system) are still susceptible to developing TB disease.</p>\r\n', 'HIV-infected individuals receiving therapy are still susceptible to TB', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hiv-infected-individuals-receiving-therapy-are-still-susceptible-to-tb', '', '', '2014-10-16 00:00:00', '2014-10-16 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/hiv-infected-individuals-receiving-therapy-are-still-susceptible-to-tb/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1047, 0, '2014-10-27 00:00:00', '2014-10-27 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">A new <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25261933\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">publication from the Malaria Genomic Epidemiology Network (MalariaGEN) in Nature Genetics</span></a>, involving <a href=\"http://www.malariagen.net/community/partner-studies/cp1-malawi\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Prof Malcolm Molyneux and others from MLW</span></a>, has assessed nearly 12,000 patients with severe malaria and over 17,000 controls were successfully genotyped to explore positive or negative host genetic associations with severe malaria.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Why do human falciparum malaria infections lead to such a variety of degrees of illness, ranging from no symptoms at all to life-threatening disease?</p>\r\n', 'Publication assesses severe malaria resistance loci in a large multi-centre study', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'publication-assesses-severe-malaria-resistance-loci-in-a-large-multi-centre-study', '', '', '2014-10-27 00:00:00', '2014-10-27 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/publication-assesses-severe-malaria-resistance-loci-in-a-large-multi-centre-study/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1048, 0, '2014-11-21 00:00:00', '2014-11-21 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Doing groundbreaking research is one thing, communicating the same to members of the general public is another as research is crammed with quite a number of medical and other terminologies that might be difficult to understand. Therefore, the Malawi Liverpool Wellcome Trust through the Science Communication Department is in the process of simplifying these messages using exhibits.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Once launched, the project will be the first of its kind in Malawi in as far as medical research and exhibitions are concerned.</p>\r\n', 'MLW research to reach more people through exhibits', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mlw-research-to-reach-more-people-through-exhibits', '', '', '2014-11-21 00:00:00', '2014-11-21 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/mlw-research-to-reach-more-people-through-exhibits/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1049, 0, '2014-11-27 00:00:00', '2014-11-27 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">PhD student Emanuele Giorgi is the recipient of this year’s young investigator award at the American Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene (ASTMH) <a href=\"http://globalbiodefense.com/event/astmh-2014-annual-meeting/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">conference</span></a> in New Orleans, USA for his presentation with moving animations of maps that show changes in malaria burden over time, aimed at fighting malaria in sub-Saharan Africa.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />He won a first tier mention plus prize money in the session.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br /><a href=\"http://10.137.18.6/index.php/component/content/article/55-malawi-liverpool-wellcome-trust/research-staff-profiles/209-emanuele-giorgi-profile.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Emanuele Giorgi</span></a> is doing a PhD in Statistics and Epidemiology at Lancaster University with supervisors <a href=\"http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/people/peter-diggle(811d7fc3-047a-40d2-89e6-c85d14a97fb8).html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Professor Peter Diggle</span></a> and <a href=\"http://10.137.18.6/index.php/component/content/article/55-malawi-liverpool-wellcome-trust/research-staff-profiles/182-terlouw-anja-2.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Dr. Anja Terlouw</span></a> from Malawi-Liverpool-Wellcome Trust clinical research programme (MLW).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'PhD student awarded prize at ASTMH conference', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'phd-student-awarded-prize-at-astmh-conference', '', '', '2014-11-27 00:00:00', '2014-11-27 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/phd-student-awarded-prize-at-astmh-conference/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1050, 0, '2014-12-08 00:00:00', '2014-12-08 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Malawi-Liverpool-Wellcome Trust clinical research programme’s (MLW) postdoctoral candidate Sanie Sesay and MLW’s associate director Wilson Mandala discussed the importance of capacity strengthening in research in Africa to tackle malaria at a meeting of the All Party Parliamentary Malaria Group (APPMG) in Westminster, London.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The APPMG is dedicated to discuss issues relevant to malaria and its control. Over the last 10 years their focus has been primarily on issues surrounding drug and insecticide&nbsp; development, insecticide and drug resistance and financing.</p>\r\n', 'MLW trainees highlight importance of research capacity building in Africa to UK parliamentary Group in Westminster', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mlw-trainees-highlight-importance-of-research-capacity-building-in-africa-to-uk-parliamentary-group-in-westminster', '', '', '2014-12-08 00:00:00', '2014-12-08 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/mlw-trainees-highlight-importance-of-research-capacity-building-in-africa-to-uk-parliamentary-group-in-westminster/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1051, 0, '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Professor Robert Heyderman, a man who has been on the steering wheel of Malawi Liverpool Wellcome Trust (MLW) for eight years as the Programme Director has left MLW.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />Rob Heyderman, a Professor in infectious diseases, received his medical training in London and Zimbabwe. After doing PhD in London, he went to Zimbabwe where for two years practiced medicine and continued his research. He went back to complete training in UK before becoming a senior lecturer and later professor in Bristol.</p>\r\n', 'MLW Bids Farewell to Professor Rob Heyderman', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mlw-bids-farewell-to-professor-rob-heyderman', '', '', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/mlw-bids-farewell-to-professor-rob-heyderman/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1052, 0, '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Cooking and Pneumonia <a href=\"http://10.137.18.6/index.php/2013-05-28-17-48-01/media-centre/357-caps-study-receives-positive-reaction-in-chikhwawa.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Study</span></a> (CAPS) is underway in Chikhwawa, Malawi. The aim is to explore whether the use of advanced cooking stoves which produce less smoke can help reduce cases of pneumonia.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br />The British Broadcasting Corporation, <a href=\"http://www.bbc.com/news/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">BBC</span></a>, talked to the Principal Investigator of the study Dr Kevin Mortimer to find out more.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.com/news/health-30448559\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Click here to read the CAPS story on the BBC</span></a>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Could a simple stove save children\'s lives?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'could-a-simple-stove-save-childrens-lives', '', '', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '2015-01-19 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/could-a-simple-stove-save-childrens-lives/', 0, 'post', '', 0);
