(3163, 1, '2020-03-27 11:06:31', '2020-03-27 11:06:31', 'Rotavirus vaccine effectiveness is higher in developed compared to low-income countries where the highest burden of rotavirus disease occurs. However, it is not known why there is a differential impact of rotavirus vaccines. Both viral and host factors could be responsible. Wide rotavirus strains circulate in low-income countries compared to high-income countries, but It is not completely understood whether the licenced rotavirus vaccines completely cross-protect against various strains and what will be the impact of vaccine use on the evolution of various circulating wild type rotavirus strains. Furthermore, the immune responses elicited through natural rotavirus infection and vaccination in not completely understood. Thus, the majority of the ongoing work by the MLW Virology Research Group focuses on understanding the viral evolution of rotaviruses circulating in Malawi and other African countries; immune responses induced by natural rotavirus infection and immunisation; and also testing the safety, tolerability and immunogenicity of the new rotavirus vaccines (RV3-BB and the P2-VP8* non-replicating rotavirus vaccines).', 'Virology', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '303-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-03-27 11:06:31', '2020-03-27 11:06:31', '', 303, 'http://127.0.0.1/303-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3164, 1, '2020-03-27 11:12:31', '2020-03-27 11:12:31', '“Professor Melita Gordon is head of the Salmonella research group, and is a clinical scientist and Professor of Gastroenterology, who has worked in Malawi on the problem of invasive Salmonella disease since 1997. The Salmonella group is focused on vaccines to save lives from 2 different clinical syndromes caused by different kinds of Salmonella; blood stream infection caused by <strong><em>Salmonella</em> Typhi</strong>, which results in <strong>typhoid fever</strong>; and blood stream infection caused by other <strong>Non-Typhoid Salmonellae (NTS)</strong>, which cause devastating severe infections in people with HIV, malaria or malnutrition, known as <strong>iNTS disease</strong>. The Salmonella group has a strong focus on mentoring and training the next generation of clinical and laboratory researchers for Malawi. Professor Gordon is a recipient of the Sir Francis Avery Jones research medal of the British Society of Gastroenterology, a previous Wellcome Trust Fellow,  and is a current UK NIHR Research Professor in Global Health. “', 'Professor Melita Gordon', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'professor-melita-gordon', '', '', '2020-11-27 13:15:33', '2020-11-27 13:15:33', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=3164', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
