(3166, 1, '2020-03-27 11:16:57', '2020-03-27 11:16:57', 'Having completed clinical training at the Royal Free, Nick Feasey specialized in Clinical Infectious Diseases and Medical Microbiology, firstly at St George’s London and subsequently spending three years in Malawi at MLW and then a year at the Wellcome Sanger Institute (WSI). Nick moved to the Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine in 2014 as Senior Lecturer, with a remit to expand tropical bacteriology research, and returned to Malawi in 2017 to establish the Bacterial And Drug Resistant Infections Group. Nick became a Professor of Clinical Microbiology at LSTM in 2019 and his research in Malawi now focuses on febrile illness and antimicrobial resistance. He holds an appointment as Honorary Professor in the Department of Microbiology at the College of Medicine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Professor Nick Feasey', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'professor-nick-feasey', '', '', '2020-11-27 13:16:52', '2020-11-27 13:16:52', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=3166', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
(3168, 1, '2020-03-27 11:18:08', '2020-03-27 11:18:08', 'The Paediatrics and Child Health group is an emerging group. The group members are clinicians with the Pediatric department at Queen Elizabeth Central Hospital and educators with the Department of Pediatrics, College of Medicine. We are committed to supporting the development of a child-centred research agenda focused on addressing the health needs of children in Malawi and addressing the SDG target 3.2. on reduction of neonatal and child mortality. Projects hosted in the PCH group represent the spectrum of clinical research at MLW including clinical trials, vaccinology, basic science and implementation science. We are committed to providing a platform for multidisciplinary collaboration in pediatric research, for which the ultimate goal is policy relevance and impact, and which we believe is necessary to address the pediatric global health agenda.', 'Paediatrics and Child Health', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '290-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-03-27 11:18:08', '2020-03-27 11:18:08', '', 290, 'http://127.0.0.1/290-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3170, 1, '2020-03-30 06:45:16', '2020-03-30 06:45:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-left\">Impact on national and international health policy and practice is key to the success of both MLW and the College of Medicine (COM). We have long-standing partnerships with key stakeholders in the health sector in Malawi and internationally, particularly in HIV, TB, malaria and rotavirus and pneumococcal vaccine policy. Several senior members of MLW sit on WHO and other policy bodies. We have a Policy Unit, partnering with the Knowledge Translation Platform in COM, the Cochrane Group in Cape Town, African Institute for Development Policy (AFIDEP), and Regional EVIPNET/WHO centres in Uganda and Zambia. The co-leads of the Policy Unit, Bertie Squire and Eliya have international experience in this domain and close involvement with Malawi. Squire leads the Centre for Applied Health Research and Delivery (CAHRD) at LSTM and Zulu is a Malawian demographer leading AFIDEP in Nairobi.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Through the Policy Unit, MLW will develop its direct role in EVIDENT, the National Evidence Informed Decision Making Network for Health Policy and Practice in Malawi supported by DFID. The EVIDENT vision is to improve the health and economic status of the country by engaging with, and facilitating the interface between the “supply” of knowledge and the “demands” of policy and practice (see figure). This communication will both represent MLW strengths and be responsive to the Malawi health sector needs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3172,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://127.0.0.1/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/policy_unit.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3172\"/><figcaption>Demand and supply in evidence informed policy making (DFID, 2012)</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', 'Policy Unit', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '