(3575, 4, '2020-08-13 15:06:33', '2020-08-13 15:06:33', 'The Paediatrics and Child Health (PCH) group was formally designated in 2016 despite a long history of MLW paediatric research beginning in the 1980s. The group members are primarily clinician-researchers with the Paediatric department at Queen Elizabeth Central Hospital and educators with the Department of Paediatrics, College of Medicine. We are committed to supporting the development of a child-centred research agenda focused on addressing the health needs of children in Malawi and the SDG target 3.2 on reduction of neonatal and child mortality. Projects hosted in the PCH group represent the spectrum of translational research at MLW including basic science (T1), early-phase studies (T2), clinical trials (T3), and implementation science (T4). We are committed to providing a platform for multidisciplinary collaboration in paediatric research, for which the ultimate goal is policy relevance and impact, and which we believe is necessary to address the paediatric global health agenda.', 'Paediatrics and Child Health', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '290-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-08-13 15:06:33', '2020-08-13 15:06:33', '', 290, 'http://127.0.0.1/290-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3576, 4, '2020-08-13 15:10:51', '2020-08-13 15:10:51', 'Our research activities include understanding the epidemiology, immunology, evolution and the disease burden of viral pathogens. We are currently investigating why rotavirus vaccines underperform in low-income settings. We are continuously assessing the effectiveness of Rotarix® rotavirus vaccine following its introduction into Malawi’s childhood immunisation program, determining the immune responses induced by rotavirus vaccination and rotavirus natural infection, deducing host factors that could be associated with vaccine responses, assessing the impact of rotavirus vaccine introduction on the circulating rotavirus strains, and also assessing the immunogenicity and efficacy of new rotavirus vaccines in Malawian children. In addition, we are investigating the origins and characterising the genetic epidemiology of SARS-CoV2 strains that are circulating in Malawi through nucleotide sequencing approaches.', 'Virology', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '303-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-08-13 15:10:51', '2020-08-13 15:10:51', '', 303, 'http://127.0.0.1/303-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3577, 4, '2020-08-13 15:16:19', '2020-08-13 15:16:19', '<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>The Salmonella group have worked for 21 years on understanding and preventing 2 serious vaccine-preventable blood-stream infection diseases, both caused by bacteria called Salmonella:\n\n1)      <strong>Typhoid fever </strong>(caused by <em>Salmonella </em>Typhi), which causes over 3 million cases of serious illness and over 33,000 deaths each year in sub-Saharan Africa. Typhoid predominantly affects healthy school-aged children (5-18y).\n\n<strong>2)      </strong><strong>Invasive non-typhoidal Salmonella disease</strong>, also called <strong>‘iNTS disease’ </strong>(caused by <em>Salmonella </em>Typhimurium and <em>Salmonella </em>Enteritidis), which cause 3.4M cases of serious illness and over 680,000 deaths annually. iNTS disease affects children under 18 months, young children with malaria, and adults with HIV.\n\n<strong>We work in 4 main areas:</strong>\n\na)      <strong>Epidemiology</strong>: to understand how much Salmonella disease is happening, how it is transmitted, and what the impact of vaccines could be\n\nb)      <strong>Host immunity</strong>: how people’s bodies make protective immune responses to Salmonella infection\n\nc)\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>a)      <strong>Bacteria</strong>: we study the genes of the bacteria themselves, to understand how they cause disease, and what drugs can be used to treat them.\n\nb)      <strong>Vaccines</strong>: We are leading clinical trials of existing vaccines, and preparing for clinical trials of new and emerging vaccines for typhoid and iNTS disease</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n&nbsp;\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>', 'Salmonella and Enterics', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '297-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-08-13 15:16:19', '2020-08-13 15:16:19', '', 297, 'http://127.0.0.1/297-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
