(3617, 4, '2020-08-14 15:30:51', '2020-08-14 15:30:51', 'We work to be a globally recognised site of international importance in reducing the disease burden due to pneumonia and meningitis pathogens.\r\n\r\nWe focus on vaccine evaluation and accelerated implementational preparedness. We strive to achieve this through excellence in clinical field epidemiology, strengthening links with basic scientists (microbiology, immunology, molecular biology) and policy makers (including social and economic science) and through fostering the professional development of emerging public health scientists in the field of vaccinology.\r\n\r\nIn recognising the health inequities between low-middle income countries (LMICs) and high-income countries (HICs), we endeavour to identify and address obstacles to achieve optimal vaccine impact.', 'Pneumonia and Meningitis Pathogens Group', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'pneumonia-and-meningitis-pathogens-group', '', '', '2020-10-19 13:55:01', '2020-10-19 13:55:01', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=research&#038;p=3617', 0, 'research', '', 0),
(3618, 4, '2020-08-14 15:29:44', '2020-08-14 15:29:44', 'Todd Swarthout is an infectious diseases epidemiologist. His research interests are in understanding how to optimise vaccine schedules to reduce the burden of vaccine-preventable diseases in low-resourced high mortality settings, and how to optimise methods to evaluate vaccine impact and effectiveness.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>Prior to his work in infectious diseases epidemiology, Todd trained in the field of forestry and natural resource conservation. Todd lived in rural coastal northern California, teaching field biology at an independent secondary school and leading a number of local environmental campaigns. One of these led to the 1999 creation of the Headwaters State Forest Reserve along California’s Redwood Coast.\r\n\r\n<strong>Affliations</strong>\r\n\r\nUniversity of Liverpool, Honorary Affliation: Senior Lecturer\r\nLiverpool School of Tropical Medicine, Honorary Affliation: Senior Research Fellow\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>', 'Todd Swathout', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'todd-swathout', '', '', '2020-11-18 11:08:40', '2020-11-18 11:08:40', '', 0, 'http://127.0.0.1/?post_type=researchers&#038;p=3618', 0, 'researchers', '', 0),
(3620, 4, '2020-08-14 15:39:15', '2020-08-14 15:39:15', '<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Our vision</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>MLW has a vision of science driving health and wellbeing in Malawi.&nbsp; This is bold, ambitious and challenging as Malawi is among the least developed economies in the world, with severe challenges related to population density, climate change and environmental degradation, nutrition, endemic diseases including HIV, TB and malaria, education and weak governmental infrastructure.&nbsp; MLW scientists have courage, commitment, energy and belief – with these combined with excellent funding, facilities and partnerships, we achieve great things.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Our mission</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The MLW Mission is to conduct high quality research to improve health and to train the next generation of researchers.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Research is  nurtured in six Themes – </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Population Health</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Social Sciences </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Maternal, Neonatal and Child Health, </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vaccines </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clinical and Experimental Medicine </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Infection Biology.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These Themes catalyse the interactions between our 15 Research Groups, 6 Associate Research Groups and three Research Support Units.  Themes are a natural transition from the previous two large programme aims which were (1) To prevent deaths in hospital and (2) to prevent disease in the community.  The change has been driven by growth, diversity and the ideas generated by a new generation of leaders.  Training in MLW is from junior scientist to Group Head and from operations staff recruit to Department Head. Nine of the Research Group Heads as well as the Director were previously trainees at MLW</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2020 Annual Group Reports</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This document describes the success, current activity and plans of the Research Groups at MLW.&nbsp; It seeks to be informative and inspirational, both for junior scientists who might choose how to join MLW, for seniors and for collaborators.&nbsp; I hope you enjoy it as much as I do.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Best wishes</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-08-14 15:39:15', '2020-08-14 15:39:15', '', 9, 'http://127.0.0.1/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
